items.title: Fertility giant to keep review secret after two IVF bungles
items.standfirst: Monash IVF said a review into the two unrelated cases was now complete but confirmed it would remain sealed to protect the privacy of the affected patients.
items.content: An Australian fertility giant will keep an independent review into two separate embryo transfer bungles a secret.Monash IVF previously apologised after a patient's embryo was "incorrectly transferred" back to her instead of her partner at a Melbourne clinic.In a different incident at the ASX-listed company's Brisbane clinic in 2023, a woman gave birth to a stranger's child following an embryo mix-up.READ MORE: Netanyahu launches extraordinary personal attack on AlbaneseMonash IVF said a review undertaken by barrister Fiona McLeod into the two unrelated cases was now complete but confirmed the full report would remain sealed to protect the privacy of the affected patients.The mix-up at the clinic in Clayton in Melbourne's south-east was blamed on a range of factors, including IT system limitations."Those limitations ultimately made subsequent processes more vulnerable to human error," Monash IVF said in a statement to the ASX.The review concluded the Brisbane incident was a result of human error.READ MORE: US destroyers head toward Venezuela as Trump aims to pressure drug cartelsIt was noted the two clinic incidents were "unrelated, different in nature and occurred some years apart"."Both cases involved non-standard IVF treatments and circumstances that would not arise in the vast majority of IVF procedures," the statement continued.Monash IVF announced in June that a patient's own embryo had been transferred back to her, instead of the treatment plan at the Clayton clinic which had designated the transfer to her partner.9news.com.au understands that patient had hoped to carry her same-sex partner's baby.READ MORE: Millions warned downpour to persist, flooding possibleA few months earlier in April, Monash IVF confirmed a woman in Brisbane had been mistakenly implanted with the wrong embryo and given birth to a child she was unrelated to in 2023.Monash IVF said it has already implemented many of the independent review's recommendations and identified more safeguards following an internal review."To the affected patients and everyone who entrusts Monash IVF with their dreams of building a family, we are deeply sorry for the distress these incidents have caused," Monash IVF Group acting chief executive Malik Jainudeen said. "We have implemented or will be implementing the recommendations of the independent review and have taken additional measures to reduce the risk of such incidents occurring in the future because the care and safety of our patients is and will always be at the heart of everything we do. "For more than 50 years, MVF has been there for patients through more than 50,000 births and we look forward to continuing to support families with their fertility journey."Monash IVF will release its full-year results next week.
